      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "c2ec90e90c17df42",
        "text": "Many endeavors to engage young people in computational thinking (CT) have been primarily through computer programming [15, 32]. Notably, early childhood is a fertile ground to cultivate young people’s interest in computing and promote their development of social, emotional, and cognitive skills [6, 12, 32, 36]. However, learning to code is challenging because 1) coding involves abstract concepts and ways of thinking that are not intuitive for beginners, and 2) many learning experiences are structured and delivered in ways that may not be productive for learners [14, 26, 44]. Much research, therefore, has been focused on introducing coding to children in engaging and personally meaningful ways [15, 52]. Given that coding typically happens in sedentary approaches in front of the screen and may reinforce the stereotype that computing is an isolated experience only focused on computers, which can be discouraging for children who love play and active learning [10, 62], some scholars have been exploring combining physical play like playground games with coding, which has shown to bring playful and engaging coding experiences [7, 39] and positively shape young children’s perceptions of what can be coding and computing [71]. Imagine the following coding scenario:"
